# Task 5 – Cybercrime Awareness Case Study & Prevention Guide

## Part A – Case Study: Phishing Scam

Phishing is a type of cybercrime where attackers trick individuals into revealing sensitive information such as passwords, bank details, or OTPs by pretending to be a trusted source. A common example involves fake emails or messages that appear to come from banks, online services, or universities.

In a typical phishing attack, the scammer first sends a message that creates urgency, such as “Your account will be blocked” or “You’ve won a prize.” The message contains a link that leads to a fake website designed to look identical to a legitimate one. When the victim enters their login details or financial information, the attacker captures this data. In some cases, the victim may also be asked to share an OTP, allowing the scammer to complete unauthorized transactions.

Students and young adults are often targeted because they frequently use digital platforms and may not always verify sources carefully. Victims can face serious consequences, including financial loss, identity theft, and unauthorized access to personal accounts. In addition, their social media accounts may be used to scam others.

Overall, phishing attacks rely heavily on human error rather than technical hacking. Awareness and caution are key to preventing such crimes.

